On the former: A local/individual context database would definitely be a big step forward, but it would be difficult for whoever was managing that database to commit to interoperability long-term. There'd be a lot of pressure to narrow/close off their API once they had achieved sufficient context aggregation. So for that reason I think of blockchains as being the better database solution for this application (with a caveat which goes to your other point) -- they provide the same functionality but with stronger commitments to interoperability distributed ownership, and virtuous protocol extensions.

The privacy/permissioning question is a big issue though, which I've written about in other contexts. If we really want blockchains to be able to give people "master accounts" that they can take with them everywhere on the internet, we need solutions for finer-grained permissioning so that people can choose which applications see which parts of their account information. And that's definitely true here -- you probably wouldn't want your cover-letter-writing-and-sending bot to accidentally ingest the complete history of your AI Dungeons & Dragons campaign.
